snippet.textDisplay: Honestly, the child alter was both sad and positively adorable at the same time. I can't imagine needing to divide yourself into multiple parts to protect yourself or trust another version of your mind to take care of and live a portion of your life for you. This portrayal of DID is both very real and seems almost magical. I personally found it very heartwarming and almost slightly comedic when Kyle switched and complained about Nin's skirt. I'm honestly glad these individuals have been able to find a safe place to talk about their alters and lifestyles and I wish them all the best in continuing to operate as systems and enjoy life regardless of how scary or difficult it may get for them.

snippet.textDisplay: Identity seemed damaging as well, and I think the thing these movies don’t differentiate is DID doesn’t mean someone is a sociopath or psychopath, those are separate mental issues. Someone with DiD could also have those issues, but seeing as it’s already a really rare disorder, it’s probably that much more rare for someone with DiD to be a sociopath or psychopath as well. Sociopathic/Psychopathic people make up about about 1% of the general population while people with DiD make up 0.01% of the general population. So having someone with an alter that has those tendencies is going to be an extremely rare case. Psychopathy is something you need to be born with so it’s more possible for someone with DiD to have that, where as sociopathy is another way the brain deals with trauma which makes it less likely because a person with DiD coped with trauma by splitting into multiple identities. It’s sad that most movies only work around this exceedingly rare occurrence of DiD that haven’t been documented yet, instead of making a movie about the struggle of DiD, which could be interesting and informative.
